Thanks for bringing this upstream _Author. Definitely agree with _Reviewer that this shouldn't be specific to the MySQL driver upstream. This patch came about when I noticed the amount of pings we did. When this patch was shipped for us, we cut QPS in half. I think this graph speaks for itself in terms of why this patch is worth the effort for large-scale production deployments: _Link I'd like to explain a couple of technical decisions as follow-ups to _Reviewer's comment and great questions: _Quote We have tests in our own test-suite for the monkey-patch, that use _Link. Toxiproxy is not supported upstream, but as an aside, I think we should strongly consider bringing it in. _Reviewer and I have talked about this in the past. We end up finding Rails bugs, especially in the ActiveRecord connection pooling logic, in many of the major releases due to extensive resiliency coverage in our own test suite. If anyone is interested in working on this, I'd be happy to help. _Quote I think that _Code remains a useful deterministic way of checking whether the database is alive. If we don't reconnect, we can't do that, and we rely on this in checking whether it was an execution error (we can ping the connection) or a connection error (we can't). _Quote Yeah, that makes sense for the general use-case. In our specific case, that wouldn't happen. _Quote I originally looked at Groupon's version, but it has a couple of problems. It parses the errors in the raw, it looks at transactions (even though it doesn't need to), and there were another couple of problems with it. The patch we use internally is a major simplification of it. Something that we also have internally that was not submitted upstream is that we only retry within a reasonable time. We saw in production 25s time-out queries that were the first of a request being retried (and the DB struggling with them twice) because there was no time-out on the _Code check.
